0.body: In this workshop you familiarize yourself with Elm. We will work project that
0.title: Goal

1.body: For this workshop we are going to need Elm. The installation page has clear instructions for each platform.
1.title: Installation

10.body:
The Elm Architecture is the way that Elm applications are organized. It boils down to the following parts Model — the state of your application View — a way to turn your state into HTML Update — a way to update your state based on messages The Elm guide has a great exposition on it, so read that before we proceed. We can start with the following skeleton, which we will refine along the way. module Workshop exposing (..) import Browser
import Html main = Browser.sandbox { init = init , update = update , view = view } type alias Model = String init : Model
init = "World" view : Model -> Html.Html msg
view model = Html.text ("Hello, " ++ model ++ "!") update : msg -> Model -> Model
update _ model = model
10.title: Elm Architecture

11.body:
For this workshop we are going to look at a COVID-19 data . Once you downloaded the dataset in JSON format you will notice that it contains records with the following information { "dateRep" : "06/07/2020", "day" : "06", "month" : "07", "year" : "2020", "cases" : 279, "deaths" : 38, "countriesAndTerritories" : "Afghanistan", "geoId" : "AF", "countryterritoryCode" : "AFG", "popData2019" : 38041757, "continentExp" : "Asia" } We will only be interested in the fields: day, month, year, cases, deaths and countriesAndTerritories. Create a type alias CovidRecord in Workshop.elm type alias CovidRecord = { day : Int , month : Int , year : Int , cases : Int , deaths : Int , region : String } We shortened countriesAndTerritories to region. We have modeled records in our data. This is different from our model though. Our model also includes state of our application. To have something to work with, we will create a model that contains a single record. init : Model
init = let record = { day = 6 , month = 7 , year = 2020 , cases = 279 , deaths = 38 , region = "Afghanistan" } in { record = record }
11.title: Model

12.body: The view function is broken. Take a look at the Workshop application to see the error message. Change the view function to show a hardcoded text.
12.title: Exercises

13.body:
We want to view our model in a tabular fashion. Because we know that we are going to view more information, for now we are going to delegate to a function that views a single record. view : Model -> Html.Html msg
view model = viewRecord model.record We will create the viewRecord next. But it is good to learn something about the Html module.
13.title: View

14.body:
The Html module has a driving principle, often seen in Elm. It describes the structure of your view by providing functions. With all most no exceptions for each HTML element there is a corresponding function. Each of these functions has the same signature. List (Attribute msg) -> List (Html msg) -> Html msg First comes a list of attributes, next the containing elements and that will produce the HTML node that the function is named after. For example, the following HTML
Hello, World!
would be generated by the following Elm code Html.section [] [ Html.div [] [ Html.span [] [ Html.text "Hello, World" ] ] ]
14.title: Html module

15.body: The Html.text function is needed to transform a String into Html.Html. If you take a look at the signature of Html.text text: String -> Html msg You will noticed that it only accepts String. So we need a way to convert our Int values into a String. Luckily the String module has just such a method: String.fromInt.
15.title: Html.text

16.body:
We want to output the following HTML in our viewRecord function.
region year month day cases deaths
Afghanistan 2020 7 6 279 38
16.title: Target

17.body: Implement the viewRecord function. Introcuce a viewRecords function that accepts a List CovidRecord. Change viewRecord to only view a single row of the table. (Hint: take a look at List.map ) What are the exception to the general rule that for each HTML element or attribute there is a corresponding function?
17.title: Exercises

18.body: Viewing data in tables, and sorting on different columns, is such a common request that people have created packages for it. The place to find packages and their documentation is https://package.elm-lang.org/ . Note that the standard library can be found here as well.
18.title: Package

19.body: The package we are particularly interested in is NoRedInk/elm-sortable-table . It promises to Create sortable tables for data of any shape Befor we can use we need to install it. We use the following command for that elm install NoRedInk/elm-sortable-table If you are curious you can look in elm.json and see that it list the package as a dependency.
19.title: Sortable Table

2.body: We will want to go the extra mile and install the following related tools as well elm-format: this will format your code according to the Elm style. elm-test: allows to test Elm code
2.title: Extra Mile

20.body: Before we can use the sortable table package we first need to update our model. We need to keep track of which column we are currently sorting on.
20.title: Updating Model

21.body: But first we are going to prepare for viewing multiple records. Change Model to hold a List CovidRecord instead of a single CovidRecord. Make sure that Workshop.elm still compiles before moving on.
21.title: Multiple Records

22.body: the sortable table package keeps track of the column to sort with the Table.State type. We need to record that state in our model to be able to let the user choose which column to sort. Before we can use the Table.State type, we need to import the module. import Table Next add a tableState field to the Model of type Table.State. Finally update the init function and provide a tableState with Table.initialSort. The argument to Table.initialSort is the column name for which we want to sort. We still needs to define does, but we will pick "Region".
22.title: Table.State

23.body: Let Model hold multiple CovidRecords. Let Model keep track of the sort state. Update the init function so the Table.initialSort is "Region".
23.title: Exercises

24.body: We are now ready to start using sortable tables. We only need to update viewRecords. viewRecords can delegate the viewing of the records to Table.view. It's signature is Table.view : Table.Config data msg -> Table.State -> List data -> Html msg Table.State and the List data we already have. So let's look at configuring our table.
24.title: Sortable Table

25.body: A Table.Config is created with Table.config . It accepts a record with three fields columns, toMsg and toId. We will look at each of those in turn.
25.title: Table.Config

26.body:
This fields configures which columns to show in the table. It is a List (Table.Column data msg). There are two convience functions that can create Table.Column that are of interest to us: Table.stringColumn and Table.intColumn. Their signatures are stringColumn : String -> (data -> String) -> Column data msg
intColumn : String -> (data -> Int) -> Column data msg The String argument will be the header of the column as well as the key in the sorting state. The next argument is a function type. It determines how to retrieve the value to show in that column from the data. For example, if you wanted to show the region one could pass the following function region : CovidRecord -> String
region { region } = region Luckily there is a shorthand in Elm. For each definition of a record type there is a corresponding accessor function. In our example that would be .region. So to create column to show the cases of a record on would use Table.inColumn "Cases" .cases
26.title: columns

27.body: We extended our Model with the current Table.State. In order to be able to change that Table.State, the Elm architecture prescribes that we should send a message The toMsg field of the Table.config argument allows you to specify that. We haven't introduced messages yet, so now is a good time to do so. type Message = SetTableState Table.State Notice that SetTableState is a function, called a constructor, takes an Table.State and returns a message. It nicely fits the toMsg signature.
27.title: toMsg

28.body:
Updating the DOM can be relatively slow, especially when huge amounts of data are changed. Elm can speeds things up with a little help. For that Elm needs to identify rows of our table. Since each row corresponds with a single record, we need to provide a function that produces a unique identifier. One way could be covidRecordId : CovidRecord -> String
covidRecordId record = record.region ++ (String.fromInt <| record.year) ++ (String.fromInt <| record.month) ++ (String.fromInt <| record.day) For more information see Html.Keyed
28.title: toId

29.body: Create a Message type with a SetTableState Table.State entry. Extent the update function with the new message entry. Store the new tableState in the model. Use Table.view in viewRecords. Note that the signature can be more concrete now. Add some more records and enjoy your sortable table.
29.title: Exercises

3.body: The elm-format repository has instructions how to install elm-format.
3.title: elm-format

30.body: Hardcoding data is great for testing purposes, but we would like to transform some JSON into our data structures. elm/json is our friend. Don't forget to install it.
30.title: Decoder

31.body:
The documentation for elm/json is extensive, since it also features in the guide covidRecordDecoder: Decode.Decoder CovidRecord
covidRecordDecoder = Decode.map6 CovidRecord (Decode.field "day" intFromString) (Decode.field "month" intFromString) (Decode.field "year" intFromString) (Decode.field "cases" Decode.int) (Decode.field "deaths" Decode.int) (Decode.field "countriesAndTerritories" Decode.string) intFromString: Decode.Decoder Int
intFromString = let mapper = Maybe.withDefault 0 << String.toInt in Decode.map mapper Decode.string
31.title: Json.Decode

32.body: install elm/json. Create a Json.Decode.Decoder for List CovidRecord. Lookup Json.Decode.decodeString and use it to populate your model.
32.title: Exercises

33.body: We now would like to fetch some real data over the network. We could fetch it directly from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC), but we don't want to hammer their servers. Remember that you downloaded a dataset in the section where we first modeled our data. We will serve from the that JSON from the reactor instead.
33.title: Getting Data

34.body: Before we can make a http call we need to install elm/http.
34.title: elm/http

35.body: This allows us to make a command to fetch our data set. Make sure that it is found at the root of your workshop project. In order to be able to make a command we need to upgrade to Browser.element.
35.title: Command

36.body: When we command for our data set, things can go wrong. The network is unreliable. The Elm Runtime should be able to tell us that information. We create a message for that occasion. I suggest Received (Result Http.Error (List CovidRecord)).
36.title: Message

37.body: Next we use Http.get to create a command to fetch the data. Http.get needs a record with two fields
37.title: Http.get

38.body: Where should the data be fetch from. This points the GET command in the right direction. /covid.json in my case, but depending on what you could your data set, this could be different.
38.title: url

39.body:
What to expect once the data is received. We are expecting JSON, so the Http.expectJson function is a good choice. The signature is Http.expectJson: (Result Http.Error data -> msg) -> Decoder data -> Expect msg This is where our new message comes in. Remember that type options are constructors, i.e. function that take its arguments and produce a message. Htpp.expectJson also needs a decoder. We already have a decoder for CovidRecord. A decoder for List CovidRecord is not far off. recordsDecoder: Decode.Decoder (List CovidRecord)
recordsDecoder = Decode.field "records" (Decode.list (covidRecordDecoder)) And that is it.
39.title: expect

4.body: A description how to install elm-test can be found on it's repository README.
4.title: elm-test

40.body: Install elm/http. Upgrade from Browser.sandbox to Browser.element. Extend Message and handle it in update. Make a Http.get call. Do proper error handling.
40.title: Exercises

5.body:
With the elm command installed we can use it to create our first Elm project. Create a directory could workshop, enter it and execute: elm init This creates the following files .
├── elm.json
└── src
5.title: First Elm project

6.body: the elm.json describes your Elm project and it's dependencies. The content is usually manipulated with the elm command, so no need to change it by hand.
6.title: elm.json

7.body: The source directory is where the Elm files live. It is empty now. Let's change that.
7.title: src

8.body: Fire up your favourite editor and open the workshop folder. In the src directory create a file Workshop.elm with the following contents module Workshop exposing (..) import Html main = Html.text "Hello, World!" That is it! This is your first Elm file.
8.title: Workshop.elm

9.body: Elm is compiled down to JavaScript. In this form Workshop.elm is inert, we can't even see what it would look like if it were compiled. There is a subcommand that will help us. Open a terminal inside the workshop directory and run elm reactor This will start an server that knows about Elm. Navigate to http://localhost:8000 . It displays the workshop directory. Enter the src directory in the browser and open Workshop.elm. You will be greeted by Elm. You can leave the reactor running. When you refresh the page it will recompile Workshop.elm and serve you the updated version.
9.title: elm reactor
